&lt;&lt;The insinuation that the American leaders sent 57,600 Americans to their deaths out of sympathy for the poor Vietnamese people is so rediculous I can't imagine someone actually saying it&gt;&gt;<br><br>
   Then the fault is in your imagination, or it's in your inability to conceive of anyone having a opinion that runs counter to your own.  Unfortunatly, people continue to think for themselves and draw their own conclusions.  Don't be so dogmatic.  <br><br>
.&lt;&lt;.... If we were truly motivated by altruistic compassion, we would not view the plight of the Vietnamese to warrant our intervention, and simultaneously consider the plight of the Nigerians to not warrant our intervention.&gt;&gt;<br><br>
     I don't know why didn't we?  <br><br>
 &lt;&lt;.... the American leaders were never moved to action out of sympathy for the Vietnamese people. They wanted to establish a puppet government loyal to Washington. &gt;&gt;<br><br>
 Then why didn't we go and establish a puppet government in Nigeria?  With our powerful Oil Companies, why didn't we.  Seems like we have more interest there then in Viet Nam.  What advantage did we gain by establishing a puppet government in one and not the other?  Why didn't we do that in Somalia, Bosnia, Haiti?????  Kuwait, Saudi Arabia???<br><br>
&lt;&lt;Nigeria is ruled by General Sani Abacha, head of one of the most bloodthirsty regimes on the planet. &gt;&gt;<br><br>
   China is right up there and we have relations with them also.  Thirty million were killed by the great famine.  Makes Nigeria look like Disneyland.<br><br>
&lt;&lt;We also have friendly relations with Burma which is guilty of horrendous human rights abuses. Tanker said in his post that this was in a different &quot;time frame&quot; than Vietnam,&gt;&gt;<br><br>
   You go on for quite a while about various &quot;no goodniks&quot; all around the world, in the far past, recent past, currntly, but I am afraid I lost your point.  Is it that we should do more, do less, do nothing?  Lost me I am afraid.<br><br>
&lt;&lt;Bush always claimed that the Persian Gulf War was fought to restore one of the only absolute monarchies on the planet. &gt;&gt;<br><br>
    He simply claimed that that country had been brutally invaded by another country and it was in &quot;our national interests&quot; to go to their aid. <br><br>
&lt;&lt;Of course we all know thast what he did was much worse, which was kill all of these people so Americans wouldn't have to pay so much for gasoline.&gt;&gt;<br><br>
   To ignore the impact on our economy of Iraq controlling all that oil is rathre immature at best.  We do have a right to protect our economy, especially when that change is bought about by armed force.  When we were hurt by the Oil Cartel, we didn't invade, or even threaten to invade them.  It was the use of armed force that triggered our--and most of the rest of the world's response.<br><br>
&lt;&lt; In the Persian Gulf War, we slaughtered 200,000 people, including 100,000 civilians, including 35,000 children.&gt;&gt;<br><br>
   Where do you get your figures--Saddam's PR press?  These are so silly, even you should be a little ashamed.  Slaughtered?  Jeez, I could have sworn I saw a lot of tanks and guys in uniform, and they weren't in their own country by the way.  <br><br>
 &lt;&lt;We weren't even there to establish that it was wrong to annex your neighbors. We killed all of these people simply so Americans wouldn't have to pay so much for gasoline.&gt;&gt;<br><br>
      Well, I am glad I know the truth now.  From your lips to God's ear.  <br><br>
&lt;&lt; Turkey is one of our tightest allies. Is this the act of a country that cares about human rights?&gt;&gt;<br><br>
      Stalin was our ally in WW 2, didn't mean we approved of him.<br><br>
&lt;&lt;In Chile, in 1970, Salvador Allende became the first Marxist ever to win a free federal election. .....United States replaced a democratically elected leader with a military dictator&gt;&gt;<br><br>
 This is a common error.  Giving to much credit to the US.  The Chilean military did it, not us.  Did we encourge them--yes, did we do it---no.  Blaming the US is all to common, especially in Latin America.  Reminds me of a joke I used to tell my Latin friends.  Three husbands--an Englishmen, a Italian, and a Latin---were asked, &quot;what would you do if you caught your wife with another man?&quot;<br>
    The Englishmen replied: &quot;I'd call the police.&quot;<br>
    The Italian replied: &quot;I'd kill them both.&quot;<br>
    The Latin replied: &quot;I'd write a letter of protest to the President of the United States.&quot; <br><br>
&lt;&lt;In the 1980's, El Salvador was ruled by a military junta led by Napolean Duarte. The junta killed at least 35,000 civilians between 1979 and 1983, including Archbishop Oscar Romero.&gt;&gt;<br><br>
   There were many atrocities committed by both sides in El Salvador.  That dosn't excuse the governments role in their Death Squads, but the other side had them also.  The situation would have been very much worse if the US hadn't stepped in.  It was our influence that brought the killings to an end, the war to an end and democracy and free elections to El Salvador. <br>
 <br>
&lt;&lt;The reason the United States fought the Spanish-American War was to try to steal this land from Spain. &gt;&gt;<br><br>
 We went to war because one newspaper whipped up Americn emotions.<br><br>
&lt;&lt; It was a land grab like the Mexican-American War, &gt;&gt;<br><br>
   If you would read your history, you would know that Mexico started the war by invading US territory.  This is taught in the Mexican schools, if not ours.  Check it out, if you don't believe me.<br><br>
&lt;&lt;The United States did not want to enter World War I. We were very strongly against entering the war. ... it reminded them of the Titanic. [Giggle]....When Americans learned of communication between Germany and Mexico, which was essentially meaningless and irrelevant, they finally relented to British and French pressure to join the war.&gt;&gt;<br><br>
    Make up your mind.  If we did not want to enter the war, we wouldn't have, regardless of the &quot;pressure.&quot;   The Germans were exerting pressure as well.  No one forced us into the war, we went because we wanted to go.  No one forced us.<br><br>
&lt;&lt;The United States did not want to enter World War II. The singular reason we finally entered the war is because Japan bombed Pearl Habor. The main reason Americans were so horror striken at the attack on Pearl Habor is because Japan hadn't declared war first,&gt;&gt;<br><br>
   How silly.  The main reason wasn't some academic legal point.  They killed a lot of Americans and were getting ready to kill a lot more.  You have an interesting, if not unique view of history, I must say.<br><br>
&lt;&lt;. If Japan hadn't bombed Pearl Habor, we would never have entered the war,&gt;&gt;<br><br>
    Now you're prophet.<br><br>
&lt;&lt; Instead, by implying that a tiny island was somehow a threat to the United States, it only made the United States look weak.&gt;&gt;<br><br>
   They rescued quite a few American Medical students there.  And in Lebonon, there were about 250 Marines killed, not &quot;several.&quot;<br><br>
&lt;&lt;There are many instances in which there is a third world conflict. It could be a war between nations, or it could be a rebellion within a nation. Each side obtains a superpower sponsor that supplies them with money, weapons, intelligence, troops, or support. Examples include Korea, Vietnam, Afganistan, Nicaragua, El Salvador, and Angola.&gt;&gt;<br><br>
   Jeff, it was called &quot;The Cold War&quot; and it was a WAR and we won it.  Really we did.  We destroyed one of the most evil, destructive and oppressive systems in history.   A systems that murdered and imprisoned MILLIONS of it's OWN PEOPLE.  <br>
    Don't believe me?  Try and find the &quot;USSR Embassy&quot; or the &quot;East German Embassy&quot; or..etc.<br>
   Millions--that's MILLIONS-- are free to form their own governments--good or bad---because of our sacrifices.  It wasn't always pretty and it wasn't always perfect, but a lot of people are grateful for our efforts.  So should you.<br>
